social_posts.post_text: 2022 was a good year. Life and research have been rather busy and fast-paced. Now is the time of year to pause work for the winter holiday and take a deep breath. I hope everyone had a pleasant year to remember. I’d like to take this opportunity to briefly reflect upon 2022.

First, this year Nehir turned two and is rapidly exploring the world: numbers, colors, animals, plants, weather, and the celestial sphere... There is a lot to wonder about cause-and-effect relationships around us, and I am so happy to share these precious moments with her.

Parenting is a curious exercise akin to riding a roller coaster, confronting waves of joy, anxiety, gratitude, and existential inquiries while simultaneously having priceless adventures and sleepless nights with your child. We survived the year and love seeing Nehir grow.

In May I had an opportunity to briefly visit the lovely city of Boston, which is full of memories of my Ph.D. and first postdoctoral fellowship years. It felt great to see friends in town during the limited time I had. I hope I can visit again and often.

2022 has also been the year when JWST started its science observations and my decade-old dream of doing science with JWST has come true! Our Department of Astrophysical Sciences at Princeton hosted awesome discussions of relevant ongoing breakthroughs in astrophysics.

One of my highlights of living in NYC has been taking walks by the Hudson River. The waves made me contemplate the Age of Discovery and the spirit of exploration Henry Hudson et al. had during their 1609 sail in search of a Northwestern route to Asia through the New World.

On some weekends, I got dizzy trying to absorb the charming paleontological content around the city mapping out the evolutionary tree of ancient reptiles. The feeding Allosaurus at AMNH was just one fascinating manifestation of the constant struggle for survival in nature.

Amidst the many skyscrapers of Manhattan, Central Park has been my habitable zone, allowing us to spend time in the green. During sunset, the skyscrapers turned into gentle reminders of the curvature of our planet and offered a fun way to estimate its radius.

One consequence of my postdoctoral fellowship at Princeton has been that I had to drive between the campus and NYC this year. Although far from being an optimal solution to an N-body problem, this long commute has allowed me to stay with family during my second postdoc.

Finally, last academic year I went through my second round of faculty applications and accepted WashU’s offer, committing to start the tenure track in September 2023. I am quite excited about my upcoming research initiatives as faculty, teaching, and other scholarly work ahead.

Looking ahead, 2023 will be a unique and exciting year as we celebrate the Centennial of our Republic of Turkey and commemorate the visionary leadership that established it, transforming the once-prosperous Ottoman Empire into a new, secular state of the people in 1923.

Off to İstanbul. ☺️

~25 years ago, my father had brought me to the Column of the Goths. This week I visited Gülhane again with my daughter and nieces, bringing back distant memories and reminding me how the vast temporal scales of our civilization made me fall in love with history and İstanbul.

Babamın sözleri hala aklımda: “Bak kuzum bu sütun Bağdat Köşkü’nden bile asırlarca daha eski. Bu şehrin önceki halklarının da sevinçleri, ümitleri ve korkuları vardı. Bu tarihi öğrenmeli ve korumalısın.” Kaidesini bile okuyamadığım bu güzel Korint sütunu boğazı selamlıyordu.

It's time to go home. This was a wonderful trip to the motherland, including a long-needed vacation, visits to inspiring historical and natural landmarks, recollection of memories, quality time with extended family, and catching up with friends.

Sağlıcakla, hoşça kal Türkiye.

3🎂... Wishing the happiest birthday to the girl who eternally conquered my heart on this very date three years ago.

Nice sağlıklı ve ufkunu genişleten yıllara, canımdan can kızım Nehir.

Today marks my last day as a postdoc as well as the end of my work at Princeton. I will miss the peaceful saunters around Lake Carnegie, hours spent hacking my code by Old Nassau, engaging Astro Coffee discussions in Peyton Hall, and inspiring visits to the IAS for the Bahcall Lunch and joint colloquia.

Today I am thrilled to embark on a journey as an assistant professor of physics. I just sat down in my office, took a deep breath, and sketched a long-term work plan. It feels great to have bold dreams full of opportunities and challenges. Let the good times roll.
Exciting early morning on campus today as we begin the 2023-2024 academic year. From freshers to finals, I wish everyone a fun year of learning and exploration!

The rise of celestial objects has been central to cultures for millennia, inspiring culture, art, and science. Today's sunrise was particularly stunning, I guess one that could be referred to as WashUhenge, where our Sun aligned with the central axis of the Danforth campus during its ascension above the horizon. As the point at which the Sun rises periodically moves North and South during a tropical year, Brookings Hall aligns with the sunrise twice, in early October and March.

34...🎂

The high eccentricity of Mars was key to Kepler's arrival at ellipses, replacing the epicycles of Copernicus, Tusi, and Ptolemy. Last Sunday, it also reminded me of my upcoming birthday as I was preparing exam questions. Here is to a new year of peace and exploration.

The last lecture of my first semester as faculty turned into a wonderful finale: closing reflections on our knowledge gaps in planetary astrophysics, some philosophical perambulations, and a heartwarming applause at the end. I am so grateful for the engagement of my students.

We are finally at the end of the Fall semester. What a wonderful start it has been... One thing that surprised me is how much “context switching” a faculty job requires. At one moment, you are the PI of a multi-institutional research project; a moment later, you manage the departmental colloquia for the next academic year; another moment later, you meet your undergraduate to go over her homework; a while later, you plan out the long-term thesis directions of your graduate students; then, you delegate group members to present in your collaboration meetings; soon after, you are writing an IDP template and code of conduct for your group; a minute later, you are the software manager of the misbehaving computing machines in your lab; before long, you find yourself reviewing postdoc applications; then you hastily write class notes to lecture during the next hour; then, you meet with your grant manager to discuss the state of your post-award funds; next you review your graduate student’s paper draft just before you finally can use your remaining precious few minutes to hide on campus and work on your own code.

Strikingly, all of these require different scientific, technical, mentorship, and management skills that Ph.D. programs do not all offer. Regardless, the first semester has been a wild ride, and I have enjoyed every moment of it.
